About Cyclistic

“Faster than walking, cheaper than rideshare, and more fun than the train.” Cyclistic is a bike share company from Chicago, conveying the spirit of “convienient, affordable, fun/healthy” by offering different types of bikes that can be found anywhere and easy to rent. For clearer overview, see presentation p. 7-9 (right click and open in browser)

goal & problem statement

Goal : Use digital / online marketing to convert casual riders to members.
Problem statement :
1. What do casual riders need?
2. How can cyclistic transform casual riders to members with digital/online marketing?
For clearer overview, see presentation p. 6 (right click and open in browser)

How the median of ride length per min changes through the week by month

all_trips_casual %>% 
  mutate(day_of_week = case_when(day_of_week == "Monday" ~1,
                                     day_of_week == "Tuesday" ~2,
                                     day_of_week == "Wednesday" ~3, 
                                     day_of_week == "Thursday" ~4,
                                     day_of_week == "Friday" ~5, 
                                     day_of_week == "Saturday" ~6,
                                     day_of_week == "Sunday" ~7)) %>% 
  group_by(day_of_week, month) %>% 
  summarise(median_duration = median(ride_length_min)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = day_of_week, y = median_duration)) + geom_line(aes(colour = month)) + labs(title = "how the ride length per min median changes through the week by month")
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'day_of_week'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.

Transfer categorical data in character to number and create reference table for later

Since there are both numerical and categorical variables, so use PAM clustering with gower distance and silhouette method.

Table with only the columns for PAM
casual_pam <- subset(casual_km, select = c(rideable_type.1, month, day_of_week.1, ride_length_min, hour_of_day))
Sample the data smaller to run the function and export table
casual_pam_sample <- casual_pam[sample(1:nrow(casual_pam), size = 5000), ]
write.csv(casual_pam_sample, file = "~/Desktop/cyclistic/casual_pam_sample.csv")
Gower distance table
casual_gower_mat <- daisy(casual_pam_sample, metric = "gower")
Find out how many cluster with silhouette method
silhouette <- c()
silhouette = c(silhouette, NA)
for(i in 2:10){
  pam_clusters = pam(as.matrix(casual_gower_mat),
                     diss = TRUE,
                     k = i)
  silhouette = c(silhouette ,pam_clusters$silinfo$avg.width)
}
plot(1:10, silhouette,
     xlab = "Clusters",
     ylab = "Silhouette Width")
lines(1:10, silhouette)

Classify all casual riders to clusters with random forest model

Create a new column for character cluster
casual_rfm <- casual_pam_sample %>% 
  mutate(cluster_ch = case_when(cluster == 1 ~"cluster_1",
                                cluster == 2 ~"cluster_2"))
Convert character to factor
casual_rfm$cluster_ch <- as.factor(casual_rfm$cluster_ch)
casual_rfm <- droplevels(casual_rfm)
Export table
write.csv(casual_rfm, file = "~/Desktop/cyclistic/casual_rfm.csv")
Split data and test accuracy
casual_rfm_index <- sample(2, nrow(casual_rfm), replace = TRUE, prob = c(0.7, 0.3))
casual_rfm_training <- casual_rfm[casual_rfm_index == 1, ]  
casual_rfm_testing <- casual_rfm[casual_rfm_index == 2, ] 
casual_rfm_test_run <- randomForest(cluster_ch~rideable_type.1+month+day_of_week.1+ride_length_min+hour_of_day, data = casual_rfm_training)
casaul_test_pred <- predict(casual_rfm_test_run, casual_rfm_testing)
casual_rfm_testing$cluster_pred <- casaul_test_pred
abc <- table(casual_rfm_testing$cluster_ch, casual_rfm_testing$cluster_pred)
accuracy <- sum(diag(abc)/sum(abc))

Accuracy (57%) is not high enough, for now just use the full data to increase accuracy (there’s actually not that big of a difference between two clusters, and both clusters already share the same possible problems, the classification is just to see how to communicate more individually to each cluster, so the accuracy can be improved later. Just wanna see the start and end station).

Run random forest
casual_rfm_run <- randomForest(cluster_ch~rideable_type.1+month+day_of_week.1+ride_length_min+hour_of_day, data = casual_rfm)

Change the categorical numbers to characters

casual_bi_table <- casual_predict_cluster %>% 
  mutate(bike_type = case_when(rideable_type.1 == 1 ~"classic_bike",
                               rideable_type.1 == 2 ~"docked_bike",
                               rideable_type.1 == 3 ~"electric_bike" ))

casual_bi_table <- casual_bi_table %>% 
  mutate(month_ch = case_when(month == 1 ~"Jan",
                               month == 2 ~"Feb",
                               month == 3 ~"Mar",
                               month == 4 ~"Apr",
                               month == 5 ~"May",
                               month == 6 ~"Jun",
                               month == 7 ~"Jul",
                               month == 8 ~"Aug",
                               month == 9 ~"Sep",
                               month == 10 ~"Oct",
                               month == 11 ~"Nov",
                               month == 12 ~"Dec"))

casual_bi_table <- casual_bi_table %>% 
  mutate(day = case_when(day_of_week.1 == 1 ~"Monday",
                         day_of_week.1 == 2 ~"Tuesday",
                         day_of_week.1 == 3 ~"Wednesday",
                         day_of_week.1 == 4 ~"Thursday",
                         day_of_week.1 == 5 ~"Friday",
                         day_of_week.1 == 6 ~"Saturday",
                         day_of_week.1 == 7 ~"Sunday"))

casual_bi_table <- casual_bi_table %>% 
  mutate(section_of_day = case_when(hour_of_day >= 0 & hour_of_day < 4 ~"midnight", 
                                    hour_of_day >= 4 & hour_of_day < 6 ~"dawn",
                                    hour_of_day >= 6 & hour_of_day < 9 ~"early_morning",
                                    hour_of_day >= 9 & hour_of_day < 12 ~"late_morning",
                                    hour_of_day >= 12 & hour_of_day < 14 ~"noon",
                                    hour_of_day >= 14 & hour_of_day < 16 ~"afternoon",
                                    hour_of_day >= 16 & hour_of_day < 19 ~"evening",
                                    hour_of_day >= 19 & hour_of_day < 21 ~"early_night",
                                    hour_of_day >= 21 ~"late_night"))

casual_bi_table <- casual_bi_table %>% 
  mutate(ride_minutes = case_when(ride_length_min >= 0 & ride_length_min < 12 ~"0_to_12", 
                                          ride_length_min >= 12 & ride_length_min < 25 ~"13_to_25",
                                          ride_length_min >= 25 & ride_length_min < 37 ~"25_to_37",
                                          ride_length_min >= 37 & ride_length_min < 50 ~"38_to_50",
                                          ride_length_min >= 50 & ride_length_min < 75 ~"50_to_75",
                                          ride_length_min >= 75 ~"over_75"))

Conclusion

Casual riders may face a lot of problems when docking the e-bikes, so they struggle and complain on social media. That is a chance for Cyclistic to make them join memberships. But it can only become a chance if the memberships can solve their problems. “E-bike memberships” are memberships that would do.There are several ways to communicate the benefits of “E-bike memberships” to them using digital/online marketing. Three of the ways would be :
* Social media ads : Solve pain points + convey “convenient, affordable, fun/healthy”
* Dialog in the app : Solve pain points + convey “convenient”
* Koc hashtag or tiktok : Attract with interesting thing + convey “fun/healthy”

To see more detailed explanation about the pain points, e-bike membership and the visualization of the 3 digital/online marketing ways, see presentation p. 17-26 (right click and open in browser)

To improve classification accuracy, I could analyze more data about person, like gender, age, family status, income… etc.

To look more into what is influencing the ride length in different timing, I could analyze more marketing data, like events, campaigns… etc.

Thank you and have a nice day.
